1
00:00:07,880 --> 00:00:11,280
No, Amy, it's definitely not
the fifth moon of Sinda Callista.

2
00:00:11,360 --> 00:00:14,040
I think I can see a Ryman's.

3
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:18,200
Amy! Amy!

4
00:00:20,880 --> 00:00:23,000
Argh!

5
00:00:25,080 --> 00:00:26,240
Doctor!

6
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:27,840
It's saying we're on Earth!

7
00:00:27,920 --> 00:00:30,040
Essex, Colchester.

8
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:38,920
Doctor?!

9
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:40,640
It's taking off again.

10
00:00:42,880 --> 00:00:44,800
Doctor, can you hear me?

11
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:46,360
Amy!

12
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:50,560
Amy...

13
00:01:00,120 --> 00:01:03,600
(ELDERLY MAN'S VOICE)
Hello? Hello, please? Hello?

14
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:09,680
I need your help.
There's been an accident.

15
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:18,280
Please, help me.

16
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:21,040
(BUZZER)

17
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:31,520
Hello?

18
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:33,360
MAN: Please, will you help me?

19
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:36,920
Help you?

20
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,800
- What's wrong?
- Something terrible's happened.

21
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:42,520
Please help me.

22
00:02:00,280 --> 00:02:02,160
Craig, what's that on the ceiling?

23
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:04,120
- What's what on the ceiling?
- That!

24
00:02:04,200 --> 00:02:06,200
It's coming from upstairs.

25
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:07,960
Who lives up there again?

26
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:11,240
Just some bloke.

27
00:02:15,480 --> 00:02:17,600
So what's the plan tonight?
Pizza, booze, telly?

28
00:02:17,680 --> 00:02:19,520
Yeah, pizza, booze, telly.

29
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:22,640
- (THUMPING AND BANGING)
- What is he doing up there?

30
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:30,480
- You put the advert up yet?
- Yeah, did it today, paper shop window.

31
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:34,800
"One furnished room available
immediately, shared kitchen, bathroom,

32
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:37,800
"with 27-year-old male,
non-smoker, £400 pcm -

33
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:39,480
"per calendar month -
suit young professional.”

34
00:02:39,560 --> 00:02:40,560
(MOBILE RINGS)

35
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:44,120
Mmm, sounds ideal. That's your mission
in life, Craig - find me a man!

36
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:46,680
Yeah,
otherwise you'll have to settle for me.

37
00:02:46,760 --> 00:02:48,320
You'll have to settle for me first.

38
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:51,080
Oh, Melina again.

39
00:02:51,160 --> 00:02:52,200
What?

40
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:54,040
Right.

41
00:02:54,120 --> 00:02:56,440
Yeah, but I've kind of got plans.

42
00:02:58,080 --> 00:02:59,560
No, it's nothing important,
it's just Craig.

43
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:02,160
- Oh, thanks, Soph(!)
- (WHISPERS) Sorry, you know what I mean!

44
00:03:02,240 --> 00:03:04,640
OK, I'll talk to Craig. OK.

45
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:08,000
Now she's having a Dylan crisis
on top of the Clare crisis.

46
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:11,840
It could be another all-nighter.
I'm sorry, but I really should go.

47
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:13,360
Do you mind if I go?

48
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:16,240
No, not at all.
No, honestly, course not, go.

49
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:18,080
- Cos I could stay.
- No, go on.

50
00:03:18,160 --> 00:03:21,720
- I mean, we've got plans.
- Just pizza.

51
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:24,240
Yeah, it's just pizza.

52
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,720
OK! Right, I'm going.

53
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:32,280
All right, then.
Well, um, I'll see you soon.

54
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:33,760
Yeah.

55
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:36,920
All right, and give me a call,
and I hope everything's OK.

56
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:38,480
Thanks, sorry.

57
00:03:42,560 --> 00:03:44,320
(THUMPING AND CRASHING)

58
00:04:01,360 --> 00:04:02,880
Just tell her.

59
00:04:02,960 --> 00:04:04,800
Just tell her, "I love you."

60
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,040
"I love you." Oh, jus...

61
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:10,360
"Hey, I don't know if you knew..."

62
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:12,360
Oh!

63
00:04:13,360 --> 00:04:16,200
(DOORBELL RINGS)

64
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:17,800
Every time!

65
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:21,520
I love you. I love you.

66
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:23,320
I love you.

67
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:24,720
I love you!

68
00:04:26,640 --> 00:04:29,000
I love you!

69
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:33,480
Well, that's good,
cos I'm your new lodger. Do you know,

70
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:36,440
this is going to be easier
than I expected!

71
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:15,520
But I only put the advert up today,
I didn't put my address.

72
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:19,160
Well, aren't you lucky I came along?
More lucky than you know.

73
00:05:19,240 --> 00:05:24,200
Less of a young professional,
more of an ancient amateur,

74
00:05:24,280 --> 00:05:26,280
but frankly I'm an absolute dream.

75
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:29,160
Hang on, mate,
I don't know if I want you staying,

76
00:05:29,240 --> 00:05:30,480
and give me back those keys,
you can't have those!

77
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:32,240
Yes, quite right. Have some rent.

78
00:05:32,320 --> 00:05:35,480
That's probably quite a lot,
isn't it? Looks like a lot.

79
00:05:35,560 --> 00:05:38,920
Is it a lot? I can never tell.

80
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:48,040
Don't spend it all on sweets. Unless
you like sweets. I like sweets. Ooh.

81
00:05:50,200 --> 00:05:52,920
That's how we greet each other
nowadays, isn't it? I'm the Doctor.

82
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:54,960
Well, they call me the Doctor,
I don't know why.

83
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:58,160
I call me the Doctor too.
Still don't know why.

84
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:00,960
- Craig Owens. The Doctor?
- Yep.

85
00:06:01,040 --> 00:06:03,520
- Who lives upstairs?
- Just some bloke.

86
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:04,760
What does he look like?

87
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:06,400
Normal. He's very quiet.

88
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:08,040
- (LOUD BANG)
- Usually.

89
00:06:08,120 --> 00:06:11,240
Sorry, who are you again? Hello?!

90
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:12,440
Excuse me...

91
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:17,440
Ah! I suppose that's...dry rot?

92
00:06:17,520 --> 00:06:20,040
- Or damp. Or mildew.
- Or none of the above.

93
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:21,640
- I'll get someone to fix it.
- No, I'll fix it.

94
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:24,040
I'm good at fixing rot.
Call me the Rotmeister.

95
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:25,880
No, I'm the Doctor,
don't call me the Rotmeister.

96
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:29,200
This is the most beautiful parlour
I have ever seen -

97
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:30,960
you're obviously
a man of impeccable taste.

98
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:32,800
I can stay, Craig, can't I? Say I can.

99
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:35,000
- You haven't even seen the room.
- The room?

100
00:06:35,080 --> 00:06:36,040
- Yourroom.
- My room?

101
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:38,920
Oh, yes, my room, my room.

102
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:41,000
Take me to my room!

103
00:06:42,400 --> 00:06:43,840
Yeah, this is Mark's old room.

104
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:45,880
He owns the place,
moved out about a month ago.

105
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,960
This uncle he'd never even heard of died
and left a load of money in the will.

106
00:06:49,040 --> 00:06:50,840
How very convenient.

107
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:53,120
This'll do just right. In fact...

108
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:55,400
(BANGING AND GLASS BREAKING)

109
00:07:00,520 --> 00:07:03,000
No time to lose. I'll take it.

110
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:05,240
Ah...you'll want to see
my credentials.

111
00:07:05,320 --> 00:07:07,520
There...
National Insurance number...

112
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:09,240
NHS number...

113
00:07:09,320 --> 00:07:10,320
References...

114
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:13,200
Is that a reference
from the Archbishop of Canterbury?

115
00:07:13,280 --> 00:07:15,880
I'm his special favourite.

116
00:07:15,960 --> 00:07:17,480
Are you hungry?

117
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:18,720
I'm hungry.

118
00:07:20,280 --> 00:07:21,720
I haven't got anything in.

119
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:27,840
You've got everything I need for
an omelette fines herbes! Pour deux!

120
00:07:27,920 --> 00:07:30,720
- So who's the girl on the fridge?
- My friend, Sophie.

121
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:32,040
Girlfriend?

122
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:33,880
A friend who's a girl.
There's nothing going on.

123
00:07:33,960 --> 00:07:35,800
Ah, that's completely normal.
Works for me.

124
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:37,920
We met at work about a year ago
at the call centre.

125
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:41,080
Oh, really, a communications exchange?
That could be handy.

126
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:42,120
Firm's going down, though.

127
00:07:42,200 --> 00:07:44,280
The boss is using
a totally rubbish business model.

128
00:07:44,360 --> 00:07:47,280
I know what they should do,
I got a plan all worked out,

129
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:51,800
but I'm just a phone drone,
I can't go running in, saying I know best.

130
00:07:51,880 --> 00:07:53,400
Why am I telling you this?
I don't even know you.

131
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:55,000
Well, I've got one of those faces.

132
00:07:55,120 --> 00:07:58,080
People never stop blurting out their plans
while I'm around.

133
00:07:58,160 --> 00:08:00,080
Right, where's your stuff?

134
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:03,160
Don't worry - it'll materialise,

135
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:05,520
if all goes to plan.

136
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:13,240
Oh, which one, which one?! No!

137
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:15,760
Why won't you land?!

138
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:22,680
Oh, that was incredible!

139
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:24,880
That was absolutely brilliant.

140
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:26,400
Where did you learn to cook?

141
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:29,320
Paris, in the 18th century.
No, hang on,

142
00:08:29,400 --> 00:08:30,960
that's not recent, is it? 17th?

143
00:08:31,040 --> 00:08:32,440
No, no, no, 20th.

144
00:08:32,520 --> 00:08:34,560
Sorry, I'm not used to doing them
in the right order.

145
00:08:34,640 --> 00:08:38,400
Has anyone ever told you
that you're a bit weird?

146
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:41,960
They never really stop.
Ever been to Paris, Craig?

147
00:08:42,040 --> 00:08:44,480
Nah, I can't see the point of Paris.

148
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:47,080
- I'm not much of a traveller.
- I can tell from your sofa.

149
00:08:47,160 --> 00:08:50,240
- My sofa?
- You're starting to look like it.

150
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:53,920
Thanks, mate, that's lovely(!)

151
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,000
No, I like it here.

152
00:08:56,080 --> 00:08:58,480
I'd miss it, I'd miss...

153
00:08:58,560 --> 00:09:01,280
- Those keys?
- What?

154
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:02,960
You're sort of...

155
00:09:05,160 --> 00:09:06,640
...fondling them.

156
00:09:06,720 --> 00:09:08,520
- I'm holding them.
- Right.

157
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,760
Anyway...

158
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:12,560
these...

159
00:09:12,640 --> 00:09:14,640
these are your keys.

160
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:16,240
I can stay?

161
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:19,240
Yeah, you're weird and you can cook -
it's good enough for me.

162
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:21,680
Right, outdoor, front door,

163
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:24,080
- your door.
- My door. My place.

164
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:27,000
My gaff. Ha-ha! Yes! Me with a key.

165
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:31,200
And listen, Mark and I,
we had an arrangement where,

166
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:35,240
if you ever need me out of your hair,
just give me a shout, OK?

167
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:39,720
Why would I want that?

168
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:42,440
In case you want to bring someone round.
A girlfriend or a...

169
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:44,680
boyfriend?

170
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:47,440
Oh, I will.
I'll shout if that happens.

171
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:49,960
Yes. Something like...

172
00:09:50,040 --> 00:09:52,880
(SHOUTING) I was not expecting this!

173
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:56,320
By the way, that...

174
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:59,440
the rot...

175
00:09:59,520 --> 00:10:01,800
I've got the strangest feeling
we shouldn't touch it.

176
00:10:09,440 --> 00:10:11,400
Earth to Pond, Earth to Pond.

177
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:15,600
- Come in, Pond.
- Doctor! (FEEDBACK HOWLS)

178
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:16,720
Ooh!

179
00:10:16,760 --> 00:10:19,200
- Sorry!
- Could you not wreck my new earpiece?

180
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:22,520
No, I mean, he seems a laugh.

181
00:10:22,600 --> 00:10:25,440
He's a bit weird.
Good weird, you know?

182
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:28,440
SOPHIE: And he just happens to have
three grand on him in a paper bag?

183
00:10:28,520 --> 00:10:29,720
Yeah.

184
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:32,960
Wait, wait. "The Doctor"?!

185
00:10:33,040 --> 00:10:35,800
Craig, what if he's a dealer?

186
00:10:38,760 --> 00:10:40,400
(CAT YOWLS)

187
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:44,960
(YOUNG MAN'S VOICE) Hello? Stop, please.

188
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:48,000
Can you hear me? I need your help.

189
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:49,800
How's the TARDIS coping?

190
00:10:49,880 --> 00:10:51,440
See for yourself.

191
00:10:56,360 --> 00:10:57,880
Ooh, nasty.

192
00:10:57,960 --> 00:11:01,680
She's locked in a materialisation loop,
trying to land again, but she can't.

193
00:11:01,760 --> 00:11:04,160
And whatever's stopping her
is upstairs in that flat.

194
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:06,400
So go upstairs and sort it!

195
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:09,160
Please. My little girl's hurt.

196
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:19,560
I don't know what it is yet.

197
00:11:19,640 --> 00:11:24,640
Anything that can stop the TARDIS
from landing is big - scary big.

198
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:28,120
Wait...aren't you scared?

199
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:31,960
I'm so sorry,
but will you help me? Please.

200
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:34,320
Help you?

201
00:11:35,840 --> 00:11:37,920
A bow tie? Are you serious?/

202
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:39,200
Hang on a sec.

203
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:41,840
What? Craig!

204
00:11:41,920 --> 00:11:43,320
Craig?

205
00:11:43,360 --> 00:11:46,840
DOCTOR: ...Orange juice, eocenes Arbuckle,
rare tarantula on the table, ooh!

206
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:49,880
I can't go up there until I know
what it is and how to deal with it,

207
00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:54,240
and it is vital that this "man" upstairs
doesn't realise who and what I am.

208
00:11:54,320 --> 00:11:55,760
So no son icing.

209
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:59,920
No advanced technology. I can only
use this cos we're on scramble.

210
00:12:00,040 --> 00:12:03,680
To anyone else hearing this conversation,
we're talking absolute gibberish.

211
00:12:03,760 --> 00:12:05,280
Practical eruption in chicken.

212
00:12:05,360 --> 00:12:08,400
Descartes Lombardy spiral.

213
00:12:08,480 --> 00:12:11,680
All I've got to do is pass
as an ordinary human being.

214
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:13,720
Simple.
What could possibly go wrong?

215
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:15,400
- Have you seen you?
- So...

216
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:17,280
you're just going to be snide?
No helpful hints?

217
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:21,160
Hmm, well, here's one...
bow tie, get rid!

218
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:22,600
Bow ties are cool.

219
00:12:22,680 --> 00:12:27,000
Come on, Amy, I'm a normal bloke,
tell me what normal blokes do.

220
00:12:27,080 --> 00:12:28,800
They watch telly, they play football,

221
00:12:28,880 --> 00:12:30,240
they go down the pub.

222
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:32,320
I could do those things.
I don't, but I could.

223
00:12:32,400 --> 00:12:34,280
- (CRASHING)
- Hang on. Wait, wait, wait! Amy?!

224
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:37,880
(SHE SCREAMS)

225
00:12:41,720 --> 00:12:43,480
Interesting.

226
00:12:44,480 --> 00:12:46,520
Localised time loop.

227
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:49,240
- (ENGINE MAKES STRANGE NOISES)
- Ow! What's all that?

228
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:53,960
Time distortion. Whatever's happening
upstairs is still affecting you.

229
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:55,840
(AMY SCREAMS)

230
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:59,600
(MORE SCREAMING)

231
00:13:02,480 --> 00:13:05,440
(STRANGE NOISES SUBSIDE)

232
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:08,880
It's stopped...ish!

233
00:13:08,960 --> 00:13:12,560
- How about your end?
- My end's good.

234
00:13:12,640 --> 00:13:17,080
So, doesn't sound great,
but nothing to worry about?

235
00:13:17,160 --> 00:13:19,680
No, no, no, not really.
Just keep the zigzag plotter on full,

236
00:13:19,760 --> 00:13:21,400
that'll protect you.

237
00:13:23,960 --> 00:13:25,280
Argh!

238
00:13:25,360 --> 00:13:28,600
- Amy, I said the zigzag plotter!
- I pulled the zigzag plotter!

239
00:13:28,680 --> 00:13:31,200
- You've got the door behind you?
- Yes!

240
00:13:31,280 --> 00:13:34,560
OK, take two steps to your right
and pull it again!

241
00:13:42,480 --> 00:13:44,360
- (ENGINE NOISE NORMAL)
- Oh.

242
00:13:44,440 --> 00:13:47,560
Now, I must not use the sonic.
I've got work to do,

243
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:49,760
- need to pick up a few items.
- Hey!

244
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:55,800
- (CAT MIAOWING)
- Ssh!

245
00:13:58,080 --> 00:14:00,240
Don't get comfortable.

246
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:09,520
(THE DOCTOR SINGS NONSENSE TO TUNE OF:
La Donna & Mobile)

247
00:14:11,600 --> 00:14:14,400
- Doctor!
- Hello?

248
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:18,840
- How long are you going to be in there?
- Oh, sorry, I like a good soak!

249
00:14:19,840 --> 00:14:22,120
(LOUD THUMPING)

250
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:24,680
- What the hell was that?
- What did you say?

251
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:29,640
I'm just going to go upstairs,
see if he's OK.

252
00:14:29,720 --> 00:14:31,240
Sorry?

253
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:45,120
What did you say?

254
00:14:51,480 --> 00:14:54,200
- ELDERLY MAN: Yes? Hello?
- Craig?

255
00:14:55,600 --> 00:14:56,760
Oow!

256
00:14:56,840 --> 00:15:00,360
It's me from downstairs.
I heard a big bang.

257
00:15:02,040 --> 00:15:04,120
No choice...it's son icing time.

258
00:15:05,160 --> 00:15:08,040
Thank you, Craig,
but I don't need your help.

259
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:12,080
Oops!

260
00:15:13,280 --> 00:15:16,320
- What happened, what's going on?
- Is that my toothbrush?

261
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:18,840
- Correct. You spoke to the man upstairs?
- Yeah.

262
00:15:18,920 --> 00:15:19,960
What did he look like?

263
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:21,880
More normal than you do
at the moment, mate.

264
00:15:21,960 --> 00:15:24,560
- What are you doing?
- I thought you might be in trouble.

265
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:29,120
(LAUGHING) Thanks(!) Well if I ever am,
you can come and save me

266
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:32,760
- with my toothbrush.
- (PHONE RINGS)

267
00:15:39,440 --> 00:15:41,600
- Ooh! Hello.
- Wah!

268
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:44,560
Hello! The Doctor.

269
00:15:44,640 --> 00:15:47,440
- Oh. Right.
- Er...you must be Sophie.

270
00:15:47,520 --> 00:15:48,920
Mm-hm.

271
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:50,240
Oh...oh!

272
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:55,840
No, Dom's in Malta, there's nobody around.
Hang on a sec.

273
00:15:55,920 --> 00:16:00,040
We've got a match today, pub league,
we're one down if you fancy it.

274
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:01,880
Pub league? A drinking competition?

275
00:16:03,080 --> 00:16:06,640
- No...football...play football?
- Football!

276
00:16:06,720 --> 00:16:09,480
Yes, blokes play football!
I'm good at football, I think.

277
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:12,920
You've saved my life! ...I've got
somebody. All right, see you down there.

278
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:14,440
Hey, Soph.

279
00:16:14,520 --> 00:16:16,880
Hey, I thought I'd come early
and meet your new flatmate.

280
00:16:16,960 --> 00:16:19,120
Do you play, Sophie?

281
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:22,560
No, Soph just stands
on the sidelines. She's my mascot.

282
00:16:22,640 --> 00:16:24,960
I'm your mascot? Mascot?!

283
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:28,400
Well, not my mascot. It's a football
match, I can't take a date.

284
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:31,440
- I didn't say I was your date.
- Neither did 1.

285
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,120
Better get dressed.

286
00:16:40,640 --> 00:16:44,000
Oh, spare kit's just in the bottom drawer.

287
00:16:44,080 --> 00:16:45,200
Bit of a mess.

288
00:16:47,400 --> 00:16:50,280
- What do you think?
- You didn't say he was gorgeous!

289
00:16:50,360 --> 00:16:53,200
You unlocked the door. How did
you do that? Those are your keys.

290
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:55,240
You must have left them
last time you came here.

291
00:16:55,320 --> 00:16:58,760
Yeah, but I...
How do you know these are my keys?

292
00:16:58,840 --> 00:17:01,080
- I've been holding them.
- I have got another set.

293
00:17:01,160 --> 00:17:02,440
You've got two sets of keys

294
00:17:02,520 --> 00:17:04,120
- to someone else's house?
- Yeah.

295
00:17:04,200 --> 00:17:05,480
I see.

296
00:17:05,560 --> 00:17:07,960
You must like it here too.

297
00:17:20,440 --> 00:17:22,800
So I'm going out.
If I hang about the house all the time,

298
00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:26,440
him upstairs might get suspicious,
notice me.

299
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:29,360
Football. OK, well done.
That is normal.

300
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:31,840
Yeah, football, all outdoorsy.

301
00:17:31,920 --> 00:17:35,560
Now, football's the one
with the sticks, isn't it?

302
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:38,520
What are you actually called,
what's your proper name?

303
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:40,080
- Just call me the Doctor.
- Yeah.

304
00:17:40,120 --> 00:17:43,400
I can't say to these guys, "Hey, this is
my new flatmate, he's called the Doctor."

305
00:17:43,480 --> 00:17:44,760
- Why not?
- Cos it's weird.

306
00:17:44,840 --> 00:17:46,480
- All right, Craig?
- Hey!

307
00:17:46,560 --> 00:17:48,440
- Hey.
- Soph. All right, mate?

308
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:51,920
Hello, I'm Craig's new flatmate.

309
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:54,840
- I'm called the Doctor.
- All right, Doctor. I'm Sean.

310
00:17:54,920 --> 00:17:57,040
- Where are you strongest?
- Arms.

311
00:17:58,240 --> 00:18:01,760
No, he means
what position on the field?

312
00:18:01,840 --> 00:18:04,440
Not sure. The front? The side?

313
00:18:04,520 --> 00:18:08,200
- Below?
- Are you any good, though?

314
00:18:09,240 --> 00:18:11,240
Let's find out!

315
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:15,680
- (WHISTLE BLOWS)
- We're going to win!

316
00:18:20,840 --> 00:18:22,240
That's not bad.

317
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:25,840
Yes. Go!

318
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:28,920
One two, one two!

319
00:18:30,800 --> 00:18:32,160
Go on, Doctor, go on, Doctor!

320
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:38,480
(CHEERING)

321
00:18:40,520 --> 00:18:42,560
You're brilliant, you're amazing!

322
00:18:42,640 --> 00:18:44,840
- Come on, Craig.
- Yes.

323
00:18:48,680 --> 00:18:51,440
Come on, Craig,
show them what you've got!

324
00:19:05,520 --> 00:19:07,720
I love this game!

325
00:19:25,600 --> 00:19:29,120
(CHANTING) Doctor, Doctor,
Doctor, Doctor!

326
00:19:39,520 --> 00:19:42,360
(CHILD'S VOICE) Please can you help me?

327
00:19:44,040 --> 00:19:46,800
Can you help me, please?

328
00:19:48,680 --> 00:19:50,240
Can you help me?

329
00:19:52,840 --> 00:19:55,680
- Hello?
- (LOCK BUZZES)

330
00:20:00,760 --> 00:20:04,200
I've lost my mum and I don't know
where she is. Please can you help me?

331
00:20:04,280 --> 00:20:06,320
Help you?

332
00:20:08,160 --> 00:20:11,240
You poor thing, what's happened?

333
00:20:11,320 --> 00:20:14,120
CHILD: Can you help me find her?

334
00:20:14,200 --> 00:20:16,640
You are soon the team!

335
00:20:16,760 --> 00:20:19,800
Next week we've got the Crown and Anchor.
We'll annihilate them!

336
00:20:19,880 --> 00:20:22,120
No violence, do you understand me?
Not while I'm around,

337
00:20:22,200 --> 00:20:24,760
not today, not ever.
I'm the Doctor, the oncoming storm...

338
00:20:24,840 --> 00:20:27,400
and you meant beat them
in a football match, didn't you?

339
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:30,520
- Yeah.
- Lovely. What sort of time?

340
00:20:31,520 --> 00:20:33,280
(THEY LAUGH)

341
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:47,960
(FIZZLING)

342
00:20:48,040 --> 00:20:50,640
- (SHE SCREAMS)
- Amy?

343
00:20:50,720 --> 00:20:52,120
Amy!

344
00:20:53,120 --> 00:20:56,400
- It's happening again - worse!
- What does the scanner say?

345
00:20:57,960 --> 00:20:59,920
A lot of nines.

346
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:02,680
Is it good that they're nines?
Tell me it's good that they're all nines!

347
00:21:02,760 --> 00:21:07,360
Yes, yes, it's...it's good!
Zigzag plotter, zigzag plotter, Amy.

348
00:21:14,320 --> 00:21:20,360
- Argh!
- Amy? Are you there?

349
00:21:20,440 --> 00:21:23,360
(ENGINE NOISE QUIETENS DOWN)

350
00:21:23,440 --> 00:21:26,840
-Amy?
- Yes, hello.

351
00:21:26,960 --> 00:21:29,960
Ah, thank heavens. I thought the TARDIS
had been flung off into the vortex

352
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:33,320
with you inside it, lost for ever.

353
00:21:33,400 --> 00:21:35,240
You mean that could actually happen?!

354
00:21:35,320 --> 00:21:37,720
- You have got to get me out of here.
- How are the numbers?

355
00:21:38,920 --> 00:21:41,040
All fives.

356
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:42,720
Fives?

357
00:21:44,800 --> 00:21:46,480
Even better.

358
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:49,680
Still, it means the effect's almost
unbelievably powerful and dangerous,

359
00:21:49,760 --> 00:21:50,880
but don't worry.

360
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:52,600
Hang on, OK?

361
00:21:52,680 --> 00:21:55,760
- I've got some rewiring to do.
- Hey! You..."hang on"!

362
00:22:04,760 --> 00:22:06,880
Hello, flatmate.

363
00:22:06,960 --> 00:22:08,800
Hey, man. Um...

364
00:22:08,880 --> 00:22:11,880
Listen, Sophie's coming round tonight,

365
00:22:11,960 --> 00:22:15,760
and I was wondering
if you could give us some space.

366
00:22:15,840 --> 00:22:18,360
Oh, don't mind me.
You won't even know I'm here.

367
00:22:18,440 --> 00:22:20,440
(DISTANT EXPLOSION)

368
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:21,680
That's the idea.

369
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:27,600
- (RATTLING AND BANGING)
- DOCTOR: Yes, perfect! What a beauty!

370
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:29,760
(RATTLING AND BANGING CONTINUE)

371
00:22:33,280 --> 00:22:35,840
- SOPHIE: That's got bigger.
- CRAIG: Oh, yeah.

372
00:22:35,920 --> 00:22:37,480
Are we going out?

373
00:22:37,560 --> 00:22:40,960
I've had a bit of a weird day.
Can we do pizza, booze, telly?

374
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:42,800
Great, love it! Wait.

375
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:46,800
No Melina, no crises,
no interruptions.

376
00:22:46,880 --> 00:22:49,560
Great. Excellent.

377
00:22:50,600 --> 00:22:52,280
Um, Soph...

378
00:22:53,720 --> 00:22:55,880
I've...

379
00:22:59,920 --> 00:23:01,680
I think...

380
00:23:02,920 --> 00:23:05,080
Where's this going?

381
00:23:06,200 --> 00:23:08,040
I think that we...

382
00:23:11,320 --> 00:23:12,920
...should...

383
00:23:14,160 --> 00:23:15,920
Mm?

384
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,560
- Hello.
- What?

385
00:23:17,640 --> 00:23:19,200
Whoops, sorry.

386
00:23:19,280 --> 00:23:21,920
Don't worry, I wasn't listening -
in a world of my own down there.

387
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:24,800
- I thought you were going out.
- Just reconnecting all the electrics.

388
00:23:24,880 --> 00:23:28,680
It's a real mess.
Where's the on-switch for this?

389
00:23:28,760 --> 00:23:31,280
- He really is on his way out.
- I don't mind, if you don't mind.

390
00:23:31,360 --> 00:23:35,080
- I don't mind. Why would I mind?
- Then stay.

391
00:23:35,160 --> 00:23:38,600
- Have a drink with us.
- What? Do I have to stay now?

392
00:23:38,680 --> 00:23:41,200
- Do you want to stay?
- I don't mind.

393
00:23:41,280 --> 00:23:43,800
- OK!
- Great!

394
00:23:43,880 --> 00:23:47,720
Cos life can seem pointless, Doctor.
Work, weekend, work, weekend.

395
00:23:47,840 --> 00:23:50,920
And there's six billion people
on the planet doing pretty much the same.

396
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:52,920
Six billion people?
Watching you two at work,

397
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:54,760
I'm starting to wonder
where they all come from.

398
00:23:54,840 --> 00:23:58,120
- What? What do you mean by that?
- So, the call centre's no good, then.

399
00:23:58,200 --> 00:24:00,000
What do you really want to do?

400
00:24:00,080 --> 00:24:03,120
Don't laugh.
I only ever told Craig about it.

401
00:24:03,200 --> 00:24:06,440
- Hmm?
- I want to work looking after animals.

402
00:24:06,560 --> 00:24:11,040
Maybe abroad.
I saw this orang-utan sanctuary on telly.

403
00:24:11,120 --> 00:24:13,600
- What's stopping you?
- She can't.

404
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:16,160
- You need loads of qualifications.
- Yeah, true.

405
00:24:16,240 --> 00:24:19,480
Plus it's scary.
Everyone I know lives round here.

406
00:24:19,560 --> 00:24:23,120
Craig got offered a job in London,
better money, didn't take it.

407
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:25,840
What's wrong with staying here?
I can't see the point of London.

408
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:30,080
Well, perhaps that's you, then.
You'll just have to stay here, secure,

409
00:24:30,160 --> 00:24:32,280
and a little bit miserable,
until the day you drop.

410
00:24:32,360 --> 00:24:34,280
Better than trying and failing, eh?

411
00:24:34,360 --> 00:24:36,760
- You think I'd fail?
- Everybody's got dreams, Sophie.

412
00:24:36,840 --> 00:24:40,080
Very few are going to achieve them,
so why pretend?

413
00:24:41,800 --> 00:24:45,760
Perhaps, in the whole, wide universe,
a call centre is where you should be.

414
00:24:45,840 --> 00:24:48,120
Why are you saying that? That's horrible!

415
00:24:48,200 --> 00:24:49,480
- Is it true?
- Of course not.

416
00:24:49,560 --> 00:24:53,920
I'm not staying in a call centre
all my life. I can do anything I want!

417
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:57,800
Oh! Yeah! Right!

418
00:24:57,880 --> 00:25:00,800
Oh, my God! Did you see what he just did?

419
00:25:00,920 --> 00:25:03,360
No, sorry. What's happening?
Are you going to live with monkeys now?

420
00:25:03,440 --> 00:25:05,200
It's a big old world, Sophie.

421
00:25:05,280 --> 00:25:08,720
Work out what's really
keeping you here, eh?

422
00:25:08,800 --> 00:25:10,720
I don't know.

423
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:12,200
Dunno.

424
00:25:19,360 --> 00:25:22,840
So, are you going to be taking off, then,
seeing the world?

425
00:25:22,920 --> 00:25:24,800
What? Do you think I should?

426
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:27,480
Yeah...

427
00:25:27,560 --> 00:25:30,560
Like the Doctor says,
what's keeping you here?

428
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:32,840
Yeah, exactly! What?

429
00:25:35,920 --> 00:25:37,920
- Bye.
- See you.

430
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:44,200
- See you in a bit.
- Yeah.

431
00:25:53,440 --> 00:25:55,160
Right. Shield's up.

432
00:25:55,240 --> 00:25:56,800
Let's scan!

433
00:25:58,720 --> 00:26:01,840
- What are you getting?
- Upstairs.

434
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:04,160
No traces of high technology. Totally...

435
00:26:04,240 --> 00:26:06,360
normal. No no, no, no.

436
00:26:06,440 --> 00:26:08,560
It can't be! It's too normal.

437
00:26:08,640 --> 00:26:11,000
Only for you could too normal
be a problem.

438
00:26:11,080 --> 00:26:13,680
You said I could be lost for ever.
Just go upstairs.

439
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:17,160
Without knowing, and get myself killed?
Then you really are lost.

440
00:26:17,240 --> 00:26:20,000
If I could just
get a look in there...

441
00:26:20,080 --> 00:26:21,440
Hold on.

442
00:26:21,520 --> 00:26:23,280
Use the data bank,

443
00:26:23,360 --> 00:26:26,480
get me the plans of this building -
its history, the layout, everything.

444
00:26:26,560 --> 00:26:29,640
Meanwhile, I shall recruit a spy.

445
00:26:52,040 --> 00:26:54,240
The Rotmeister...

446
00:26:55,320 --> 00:26:56,480
Ah!

447
00:26:56,560 --> 00:26:58,000
Oow!

448
00:27:03,920 --> 00:27:05,400
Craig!

449
00:27:06,440 --> 00:27:10,320
Craig. (KICKS DOOR)
Breakfast. It's normal.

450
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:11,880
Craig?

451
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:15,640
Craig!

452
00:27:17,480 --> 00:27:20,880
Craig, I told you not to touch it!
What's that?

453
00:27:20,960 --> 00:27:23,280
An unfamiliar
and obviously poisonous substance.

454
00:27:23,400 --> 00:27:26,720
"Oh, I know what would be really clever -
I'll stick my hand in it!"

455
00:27:26,800 --> 00:27:28,640
Come on, Craig, breathe.

456
00:27:30,080 --> 00:27:33,840
Come on, Craig, breathe!
Thems are healthy footballer's lungs!

457
00:27:34,760 --> 00:27:36,720
Right. Reverse the enzyme decay.

458
00:27:36,800 --> 00:27:39,560
Excite the tannin molecules.

459
00:27:50,120 --> 00:27:53,600
- I've got to go to work.
- On no account. You need rest.

460
00:27:53,680 --> 00:27:55,160
One more.

461
00:28:01,200 --> 00:28:03,800
It's the planning meeting, it's important.

462
00:28:03,880 --> 00:28:04,960
You're important.

463
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:09,880
You're going to be fine, Craig.

464
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:26,400
What?!

465
00:28:26,480 --> 00:28:29,440
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no!

466
00:28:42,120 --> 00:28:43,360
Oh, afternoon.

467
00:28:43,440 --> 00:28:46,320
I'm so sorry, Michael,
I don't know what happened.

468
00:28:46,400 --> 00:28:48,000
- I've got no excuse.
- I'm afraid

469
00:28:48,120 --> 00:28:50,360
that's not what my screen is telling me,
Mr Lang.

470
00:28:50,440 --> 00:28:51,720
(ANGRY VOICE ON HEADSET)

471
00:28:51,800 --> 00:28:53,840
What's he doing here?
What are you doing here?

472
00:28:53,960 --> 00:28:57,640
If that's your attitude, Mr Lang,
I suggest you take your custom elsewhere.

473
00:28:57,720 --> 00:28:59,960
- (BLOWS RASPBERRY)
- No, no! That's one of my best clients!

474
00:29:00,040 --> 00:29:02,400
Hello, Craig, how are you feeling?
Had some time to kill.

475
00:29:02,520 --> 00:29:05,000
I was curious, never worked in an office.
Never worked in anywhere.

476
00:29:05,080 --> 00:29:06,200
You're insane!

477
00:29:06,280 --> 00:29:08,080
Leave off the Doctor,
I love the Doctor.

478
00:29:08,160 --> 00:29:10,440
He was brilliant
in the planning meeting.

479
00:29:10,520 --> 00:29:12,280
You went to the planning meeting?

480
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:16,280
Yes. I was your representative. We don't
need Mr Lang any more. Rude Mr Lang.

481
00:29:16,360 --> 00:29:18,200
Here you go,
and I found some custard creams.

482
00:29:18,280 --> 00:29:19,640
Sophie, my hero.

483
00:29:19,720 --> 00:29:22,640
Hi, Craig. I went on the web,
applied for a wildlife charity thing.

484
00:29:22,720 --> 00:29:25,200
They said I could always start
as a volunteer straightaway.

485
00:29:25,280 --> 00:29:28,600
- Should I do it?
- Yeah, great, yeah, good, go for it.

486
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:30,560
You look awful.
About turn! Bed. Now.

487
00:29:30,640 --> 00:29:34,560
- Who next? Oh, yes.
- (MALE VOICE ON HEADSET)

488
00:29:34,640 --> 00:29:40,120
Hello, Mr Joergensen. Can you hold?
I have to eat a biscuit.

489
00:29:57,680 --> 00:29:59,960
What the hell...?

490
00:30:01,400 --> 00:30:02,480
(CAT MIAOWS)

491
00:30:04,560 --> 00:30:06,560
Have you been upstairs?

492
00:30:06,640 --> 00:30:08,080
Yes?

493
00:30:08,160 --> 00:30:10,760
(THROATY MIAOW)

494
00:30:13,240 --> 00:30:16,280
You can do it. Show me what's up there.
What's behind that door?

495
00:30:16,360 --> 00:30:17,640
Try to show me.

496
00:30:17,720 --> 00:30:20,360
Oh, that doesn't make sense!
Ever see anyone go up there?

497
00:30:20,440 --> 00:30:22,680
Lots of people? Good, good.
What kind of people?

498
00:30:22,760 --> 00:30:25,120
- Miaow.
- People who never came back down.

499
00:30:25,200 --> 00:30:26,920
That's bad. That's very bad.

500
00:30:29,520 --> 00:30:31,360
(CAT MIAOWS)

501
00:30:31,440 --> 00:30:33,800
- Oh, hello.
- I can't take this any more.

502
00:30:33,880 --> 00:30:35,160
I want you to go!

503
00:30:37,520 --> 00:30:40,040
- You can have this back, an' all.
- What have I done?

504
00:30:40,120 --> 00:30:43,280
- For a start, talking to a cat.
- Lots of people talk to cats.

505
00:30:43,400 --> 00:30:46,080
Everybody loves you, and you're better
at football than me, and my job,

506
00:30:46,160 --> 00:30:51,480
and now Sophie's all, "Oh, monkeys,
monkeys!" And then...there's that!

507
00:30:51,560 --> 00:30:53,760
It's art! A statement on modern society.

508
00:30:53,840 --> 00:30:57,920
- "Ooh, ain't modern society awful?"
- Me and you, it's not going to work.

509
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:00,360
You've been here three days,
the three weirdest days of my life.

510
00:31:00,480 --> 00:31:03,840
- Your days will get much weirder if I go.
- I thought it was good weird. It's bad.

511
00:31:03,920 --> 00:31:05,360
- I can't do this!
- I can't leave.

512
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:06,960
Like you, I can't see the point
of anywhere else.

513
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:10,800
- Madrid, ha, what a dump! I have to stay.
- No, you don't, you have to leave!

514
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:12,680
- I can't go!
- Just get out!

515
00:31:12,800 --> 00:31:16,800
Right! Only way. I'm going to show you
something, but ssh, really, ssh!

516
00:31:16,880 --> 00:31:19,280
Oh, I am going to regret this.
OK, right...

517
00:31:19,360 --> 00:31:21,960
- First, general background!
- Yargh!

518
00:31:25,120 --> 00:31:27,400
Oh!

519
00:31:27,480 --> 00:31:29,240
Oow!

520
00:31:29,320 --> 00:31:31,120
- You're a...
- Yes.

521
00:31:31,200 --> 00:31:33,080
- From...
- Ssh.

522
00:31:33,160 --> 00:31:34,920
- You've got a TARDIS!
- Yes. Ssh!

523
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:36,120
Eleventh!

524
00:31:36,200 --> 00:31:38,560
Right... OK, specific detail.

525
00:31:38,640 --> 00:31:40,200
BOTH: Argh!

526
00:31:42,520 --> 00:31:43,960
Amy! Amy!

527
00:31:47,080 --> 00:31:48,480
You saw my ad

528
00:31:48,560 --> 00:31:51,040
- in the paper shop window.
- Yes, with this right above it.

529
00:31:51,160 --> 00:31:55,520
Which is odd, because Amy hasn't written
it yet. Time travel, it can happen.

530
00:31:55,600 --> 00:31:57,880
That's a scanner! You've used...

531
00:31:57,960 --> 00:32:01,160
non-technological technology
of Lammasteen.

532
00:32:01,240 --> 00:32:03,080
(SHOUTS) Shut up!

533
00:32:13,240 --> 00:32:15,320
CHILD: Please can you help me?

534
00:32:16,400 --> 00:32:17,800
Hi.

535
00:32:17,880 --> 00:32:22,720
- Please. Will you help me?
- What's the matter, my love?

536
00:32:22,800 --> 00:32:25,640
Help you?

537
00:32:29,240 --> 00:32:30,840
Argh!

538
00:32:30,920 --> 00:32:35,800
I am never, never doing that
ever, ever again... Amy!

539
00:32:35,880 --> 00:32:37,080
That's Amy Pond!

540
00:32:37,160 --> 00:32:41,720
Oh, of course, you can understand us
now, hurrah(!) ...Got those plans yet?

541
00:32:44,600 --> 00:32:46,880
- Still searching for them.
- I've worked it out

542
00:32:46,960 --> 00:32:49,040
- with psychic help from a cat.
- Cat?

543
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:51,960
Yes. I know he's got a time engine
in the flat upstairs.

544
00:32:52,040 --> 00:32:53,880
He's using innocent people
to try and launch it.

545
00:32:53,960 --> 00:32:56,000
Whenever he does, they get burnt up,
hence the stain...

546
00:32:56,080 --> 00:32:58,200
- From the ceiling.
- Well done, Craig.

547
00:32:58,280 --> 00:33:00,160
And you, Miss Pond, nearly get thrown off

548
00:33:00,240 --> 00:33:01,600
- into the Vortex.
- Lovely.

549
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:04,040
- (SMASH)
- People are dying up there!

550
00:33:04,120 --> 00:33:06,640
People are dying... People are dying...
People are dying... People are dying...

551
00:33:06,720 --> 00:33:09,040
- Amy!
- (SCREAMS) Doctor!

552
00:33:09,120 --> 00:33:11,480
They're being killed!

553
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:13,120
- Someone's up there.
- Oh, my...!

554
00:33:13,200 --> 00:33:15,400
(ENGINE GOES HAYWIRE)

555
00:33:17,560 --> 00:33:19,920
Doctor! Hang on!

556
00:33:21,520 --> 00:33:24,160
Craig, come on -
someone's dying up there.

557
00:33:25,120 --> 00:33:29,040
It's Sophie. It's Sophie
that's dying up there, it's Sophie!/

558
00:33:29,120 --> 00:33:31,280
Doctor! Argh!

559
00:33:31,360 --> 00:33:33,720
- Where's Sophie?
- Wait, wait!

560
00:33:33,800 --> 00:33:35,880
-Amy?
- Are you upstairs?

561
00:33:35,960 --> 00:33:37,120
- Just going in.
- You can't be upstairs.

562
00:33:37,200 --> 00:33:39,200
- Of course I can be upstairs!
- Come on!

563
00:33:39,280 --> 00:33:43,280
No! I've got the plans. You cannot be
upstairs, it's a one-storey building.

564
00:33:43,360 --> 00:33:45,520
There is no upstairs!

565
00:33:52,800 --> 00:33:54,640
What?

566
00:33:56,240 --> 00:33:59,840
- What?
- Oh. Oh, of course!

567
00:34:01,280 --> 00:34:04,720
The time engine isn't in the flat.
The time engine is the flat -

568
00:34:04,800 --> 00:34:07,920
someone's attempt to build a TARDIS.

569
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:10,160
No, there's always been an upstairs.

570
00:34:10,240 --> 00:34:12,720
- Has there? Think about it.
- Yes.

571
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:14,000
No. I don't...

572
00:34:14,080 --> 00:34:17,160
Perception filter. It's more than
a disguise. It tricks your memory.

573
00:34:17,240 --> 00:34:18,960
- (SCREAMING)
- Sophie!

574
00:34:19,040 --> 00:34:21,080
Sophie! Oh, my God, Sophie!

575
00:34:21,160 --> 00:34:23,400
- Craig!
- It's controlling her. It's willing her

576
00:34:23,480 --> 00:34:26,440
- to touch the activator.
- It's not going to have her!

577
00:34:26,520 --> 00:34:28,200
SOPHIE: Argh!

578
00:34:28,280 --> 00:34:30,880
- Ah! Deadlock seal!
- You've got to do something!

579
00:34:33,240 --> 00:34:36,360
What? Why's it let her go?

580
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:45,000
- You will help me.
- Right! Stop!

581
00:34:45,080 --> 00:34:46,240
Crashed ship, let's see.

582
00:34:46,320 --> 00:34:48,600
Hello. I'm Captain Troy Handsome
of International Rescue.

583
00:34:48,680 --> 00:34:50,280
Please state the nature of your emergency.

584
00:34:50,360 --> 00:34:52,080
The ship has crashed. The crew are dead.

585
00:34:52,200 --> 00:34:55,120
- A pilot is required.
- You're the emergency crash program.

586
00:34:55,240 --> 00:34:58,280
A hologram. What? You've been luring
people up here so you can try them out?

587
00:34:58,360 --> 00:35:00,640
(MULTIPLE VOICES) You will help me,
you will help me, you will help me.

588
00:35:00,720 --> 00:35:02,160
Craig! Where am I?

589
00:35:02,200 --> 00:35:05,280
Hush! ...Human brains aren't strong
enough, they just burn, but you're stupid.

590
00:35:05,360 --> 00:35:09,160
- You just keep trying.
- 17 people have been tried.

591
00:35:09,240 --> 00:35:13,800
- 6,000,400,026 remain.
- Seriously, what is going on?

592
00:35:13,920 --> 00:35:17,320
Oh, for goodness' sake! The top floor of
Craig's building is an alien spaceship,

593
00:35:17,400 --> 00:35:19,360
intent on slaughtering
the population of this planet.

594
00:35:19,440 --> 00:35:20,880
Any questions? No, good.

595
00:35:20,920 --> 00:35:23,880
- Yes, I have questions.
- The correct pilot has now been found.

596
00:35:23,960 --> 00:35:25,640
Yes, I was worried you'd say that.

597
00:35:25,720 --> 00:35:27,200
He means you, Doctor, doesn't he?

598
00:35:27,280 --> 00:35:29,280
The correct pilot has been found.

599
00:35:29,360 --> 00:35:33,480
The correct pilot has been found.
The correct pilot has been found.

600
00:35:33,560 --> 00:35:34,920
What's happening?

601
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:38,280
- It's pulling me in! I'm the new pilot!
- Could you do it?

602
00:35:38,360 --> 00:35:40,600
Could you fly the ship safely?

603
00:35:40,680 --> 00:35:43,720
No, I'm way too much for this ship.
My hand touches that panel,

604
00:35:43,800 --> 00:35:46,720
the planet doesn't blow up,
the whole solar system does.

605
00:35:46,800 --> 00:35:48,840
The correct pilot has been found.

606
00:35:48,920 --> 00:35:51,600
No...worst choice ever,
I promise you. Stop this!

607
00:35:51,680 --> 00:35:53,720
Doctor, it's getting worse.

608
00:35:53,800 --> 00:35:56,760
It doesn't want everyone.
Craig, it didn't want you!

609
00:35:56,840 --> 00:35:58,880
I spoke to him and he said
I couldn't help him!

610
00:35:58,960 --> 00:36:01,800
It didn't want Sophie before today,
but now it does. What's changed?

611
00:36:01,880 --> 00:36:03,280
Argh! No!

612
00:36:03,360 --> 00:36:06,560
I gave her the idea of leaving!
It's a machine that needs to leave.

613
00:36:06,640 --> 00:36:09,800
It wants people who want to escape,
and you don't want to leave, Craig.

614
00:36:09,880 --> 00:36:12,240
- You're Mr Sofa Man.
- Doctor!

615
00:36:12,320 --> 00:36:13,880
Craig, you can shut down the engine.

616
00:36:13,960 --> 00:36:17,320
Put your hand on the panel and
concentrate on why you want to stay!

617
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:19,120
- Craig, no!
- Will it work?

618
00:36:19,200 --> 00:36:19,960
- Yes!
- Are you sure?

619
00:36:20,040 --> 00:36:21,640
- Yes!
- Is that a lie?

620
00:36:21,720 --> 00:36:23,160
Of course it's a lie!

621
00:36:23,240 --> 00:36:26,000
It's good enough for me. Geronimo!

622
00:36:26,080 --> 00:36:28,120
(CRAIG SCREAMS)

623
00:36:28,200 --> 00:36:29,680
(AMY SCREAMS)

624
00:36:29,760 --> 00:36:32,120
- SOPHIE: Craig!
- Doctor!

625
00:36:32,200 --> 00:36:34,240
Craig, what's keeping you here?

626
00:36:34,360 --> 00:36:38,280
Think about everything that makes you want
to stay here! Why don't you want to leave?

627
00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:40,720
Sophie! I don't want to leave Sophie!

628
00:36:40,800 --> 00:36:42,800
I can't leave Sophie! I love Sophie!

629
00:36:45,680 --> 00:36:47,560
I love you, too, Craig, you idiot!

630
00:36:49,240 --> 00:36:51,200
- Doctor!
- Honestly, do you mean that?

631
00:36:51,320 --> 00:36:54,520
- Of course I mean it! Do you mean it?
- I've always meant it. Seriously, though,

632
00:36:54,600 --> 00:36:56,080
- do you mean it?
- Yes.

633
00:36:56,160 --> 00:36:57,760
- Ugh!
- What about the monkeys?

634
00:36:57,840 --> 00:37:00,760
Oh, not now, not again!
Craig, the planet's about to burn!

635
00:37:00,840 --> 00:37:02,880
For God's sake, kiss the girl!

636
00:37:02,960 --> 00:37:04,480
Kiss the girl!

637
00:37:10,080 --> 00:37:13,640
(ENGINE RETURNS TO NORMAL RUNNING)

638
00:37:15,520 --> 00:37:17,480
Doctor!

639
00:37:17,560 --> 00:37:19,480
You've done it.

640
00:37:19,560 --> 00:37:21,920
Ha-ha!

641
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:23,680
You've done it! Oh...

642
00:37:23,800 --> 00:37:27,440
now the screen's just zeros...now it's
minus ones, minus twos, minus threes...

643
00:37:27,520 --> 00:37:28,480
Big yes!

644
00:37:28,560 --> 00:37:31,960
(MULTIPLE VOICES) Help me.
Help me. Help me. Help me.

645
00:37:32,040 --> 00:37:34,520
- Big no.
- Help me. Help me. Help me.

646
00:37:34,600 --> 00:37:36,800
- Help me. Help me. Help me.
- Did we switch it off?

647
00:37:36,880 --> 00:37:41,200
Emergency shutdown. It's imploding.
Everybody out, out, out!

648
00:37:41,280 --> 00:37:45,360
Help me. Help me. Help me.
Help me. Help me.

649
00:37:45,440 --> 00:37:47,120
Help me. Help me. Help me.

650
00:37:47,200 --> 00:37:49,520
- Doctor!
- Help me. Help me. Help me...

651
00:38:10,640 --> 00:38:11,720
(BIRDSONG)

652
00:38:11,800 --> 00:38:16,720
Look at them. Didn't they see that?
The whole top floor just vanished.

653
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:19,880
Perception filter.
There never was a top floor.

654
00:38:23,120 --> 00:38:26,080
(KISSING AND SIGHS OF PLEASURE)

655
00:38:31,960 --> 00:38:35,240
- Have we spoiled our friendship, then?
- Totally ruined it.

656
00:38:35,320 --> 00:38:36,920
And what about the monkeys?

657
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:39,040
We could save them together,
you know.

658
00:38:39,120 --> 00:38:41,000
Do whatever we want.

659
00:38:41,080 --> 00:38:43,880
I could see the point of Paris
if you were there with me.

660
00:38:43,960 --> 00:38:46,760
First, let's destroy our friendship
completely.

661
00:39:00,160 --> 00:39:03,280
- Oi!
- What, you're trying to sneak off?

662
00:39:03,360 --> 00:39:05,040
Yes, well, you were sort of...

663
00:39:05,120 --> 00:39:06,840
busy.

664
00:39:09,240 --> 00:39:11,000
I want you to keep these.

665
00:39:12,160 --> 00:39:15,920
Thank you. Cos I might pop back soon,
have another little stay.

666
00:39:16,040 --> 00:39:20,240
No, you won't. I've been in your head,
remember? I still want you to keep them.

667
00:39:21,800 --> 00:39:22,960
Thank you, Craig.

668
00:39:23,040 --> 00:39:24,760
Thank you, Doctor.

669
00:39:24,840 --> 00:39:26,080
Sophie.

670
00:39:26,160 --> 00:39:30,280
Now, then.
6,000,400,026 people in the world.

671
00:39:30,360 --> 00:39:33,120
That's the number to beat.

672
00:39:34,280 --> 00:39:35,360
Yeah.

673
00:39:59,720 --> 00:40:04,160
Back in time! You need to go to
the paper shop, leave that note for me.

674
00:40:04,240 --> 00:40:07,800
Right little matchmaker, aren't you?
Can't you find me a fella?

675
00:40:07,880 --> 00:40:09,560
Oh, rectifier's playing up again...

676
00:40:09,640 --> 00:40:13,080
Hold on. You write the note,
and I'll change that will.

677
00:40:13,160 --> 00:40:15,520
- You got a pen?
- Make sure it's a red pen.

